	<table cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#000000" width="470">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<table cellpadding="10" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" width="468">
					<tr>
						<td>
							<b>Effective Business Strategies for Today's Marketplace</b><br />
							The Business track provides a thorough 
understanding of the industry's current business 
trends, the most successful business models in 
play today, and what economic factors are likely 
to drive the game industry of tomorrow. Learn how 
to read and reach the marketplace, where new 
sources for funding can be found, and how a 
design studio - or any business in the 
interactive space -- can thrive in these 
challenging and competitive times.
</td>
					</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		</tr>
	</table>

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="27"></a>3.1 - Reaching the New Gamer</b><br />
		Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:00 AM<br />
		Room: 406AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		With 60 percent of gamers now over 18, it’s only 
a matter of time before that age skews older – 
and older. Sooner or later, this shift in 
demographics will force publishers to release 
content to meet the demand of these new, more 
mature consumers. How will the market expand and 
what demographic groups will dominate? What 
genres will survive, what genres will fade away, 
and what new genres will be created? How can 
developers and publishers target their message to 
the right audience for a given title? And how 
should the industry react to the growing 
popularity of mature-themed games.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
			<tr>
				<td valign="top">Moderator:</td>
				<td>&nbsp;</td>
				<td valign="top">
					
						  Jason Rubin,&nbsp;Naughty Dog, Inc.&nbsp;<br />
					
				</td>
			</tr>
		
	
	
			<tr>
				<td valign="top">Panelist:</td>
				<td>&nbsp;</td>
				<td valign="top">
					
						  Vince Broady,&nbsp;GameSpot&nbsp;<br />
					
				</td>
			</tr>
		
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="28"></a>3.2 - Marketing Solutions for Every Budget</b><br />
		Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 11:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;1:00 PM<br />
		Room: 406AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		How do you create and execute an effective 
marketing and promotion campaign that works with 
your game’s unique content and company’s fixed 
budget? Maybe    you want your ads on network TV, 
but can you afford it? You might want your game 
previewed in Time and Entertainment Weekly, but 
do you know who to call? And how would you 
narrowcast a message to the enthusiast community 
for a game that is too niche for mainstream press 
or TV? A panel of marketing experts will use 
three hypothetical budgets – $20,000, $250,000, 
and $1 million -- and discuss the best methods to 
promote a game, create brand awareness, and drive 
sales within the limitations of each.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
			<tr>
				<td valign="top">Panelist:</td>
				<td>&nbsp;</td>
				<td valign="top">
					
						  Liz Allen,&nbsp;LucasArts Entertainment&nbsp;<br />
					
				</td>
			</tr>
		
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="29"></a>3.3 - Analyst Roundtable: How they Work, What they Know</b><br />
		Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 1:30 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:00 PM<br />
		Room: 406AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		You spend your time making games, they spend 
their time analyzing the marketplace. Isn’t it 
time you listened to what they have to say about 
which publishers have the best strategies, which 
platforms will find traction with consumers, and 
what retail models will prevail? Hear from the 
industry's top analysts as they discuss where the 
game business is headed. Understand their 
methodologies (to better analyze the marketplace 
yourself) as you hear them assess trends, sales 
figures, and industry growth.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
			<tr>
				<td valign="top">Moderator:</td>
				<td>&nbsp;</td>
				<td valign="top">
					
						  Alex Pham,&nbsp;Los Angeles Times&nbsp;<br />
					
				</td>
			</tr>
		
	
	
			<tr>
				<td valign="top">Panelist:</td>
				<td>&nbsp;</td>
				<td valign="top">
					
						  Richard Ow,&nbsp;NPD/Funworld&nbsp;<br />
					
						  Michael Pachter,&nbsp;Wedbush Morgan Securities&nbsp;<br />
					
						  Edward Williams,&nbsp;Gerard Klauer Mattison&nbsp;<br />
					
				</td>
			</tr>
		
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="30"></a>3.4 - Start-up Summit: How to Market Your Talent and Focus Your Business Strategy</b><br />
		Thursday, May 15, 2003, 9:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;10:30 AM<br />
		Room: 406AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		Changes to funding, development, distribution, 
and marketing means yesterday's start-up 
strategies may not work in the current market. 
This session will advise attendees how to 
structure a start-up development studio that 
takes advantage of current marketplace realities. 
Topics covered will include what publishers look 
for from development partners, how small- to mid-
size studios and businesses can take advantage of 
the outsourcing needs of larger, more traditional 
publishers and developers, how direct developer 
licensing deals work, the way work-for-hire deals 
are creating new opportunities for small-scale 
companies, and, in general, where opportunities 
exist for the smart and talented enterprise. 
Developers and content creators will walk away 
knowing how to position their business for 
success and how to give themselves the best 
chance at succeeding as an independent studio.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
			<tr>
				<td valign="top">Moderator:</td>
				<td>&nbsp;</td>
				<td valign="top">
					
						  Aaron Loeb,&nbsp;Planet Moon Studios&nbsp;<br />
					
				</td>
			</tr>
		
	
	
			<tr>
				<td valign="top">Panelist:</td>
				<td>&nbsp;</td>
				<td valign="top">
					
						  Jeff Butler,&nbsp;Sigil&nbsp;<br />
					
						  Tim Morten,&nbsp;Savage Entertainment&nbsp;<br />
					
						  James Schmalz,&nbsp;Digital Extremes&nbsp;<br />
					
				</td>
			</tr>
		
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="31"></a>3.5 - Taking a Lesson from the Boom in Sports Games</b><br />
		Thursday, May 15, 2003, 11:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;12:30 PM<br />
		Room: 406AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		As a genre, sports sims drive the game industry. 
The genre not only outsells all others, its 
revenue for the past 5 years (through 2002) is 
trending to more than double, yet the games come 
in for very little scrutiny. This panel of top-
selling sports sim producers will discuss their 
methods, share their expertise, and discuss ways 
publishers and developers of other genres can 
learn from their acquired wisdom. Learn how 
intelligent use of licenses, a creative approach 
to sequels, having a structure that encourages 
and uses player feedback, and original (and 
sometimes over-the-top) marketing can drive huge 
revenues toward anyone’s bottom line.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
			<tr>
				<td valign="top">Panelist:</td>
				<td>&nbsp;</td>
				<td valign="top">
					
						  John Schappert,&nbsp;Electronic Arts&nbsp;<br />
					
						  Greg Thomas,&nbsp;Sega of America/Visual Concepts&nbsp;<br />
					
				</td>
			</tr>
		
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="32"></a>3.6 - Grow Your Career in the Game Industry</b><br />
		Thursday, May 15, 2003, 2:00 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:30 PM<br />
		Room: 406AB<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		As the games evolve, so do the skill sets 
required to maintain those games' high technical 
and creative standards. Understand the growing 
importance of skills including server 
engineering, digital effects and adaptive audio 
expertise, art skills outside of computer art 
(sculpture, painting, musical composition), and 
you are on your way to growing and solidifying 
your standing in the industry. Attendees will 
learn what skills are in demand now, and what 
skills will be required to support the onslaught 
of massively-multiplayer, console, mobile, PC and 
web games due in the coming years.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
			<tr>
				<td valign="top">Moderator:</td>
				<td>&nbsp;</td>
				<td valign="top">
					
